<body>
  <h1>DevOps Glossary</h1>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Term</th>
        <th>Description</th>
        <th>Reference</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <!-- 1. CI/CD -->
      <tr>
        <td>CI/CD</td>
        <td>A DevOps practice that emphasizes automating the process of integrating code changes into a shared repository (Continuous Integration) and deploying code to production automatically (Continuous Deployment). It enables frequent releases, rapid feedback, and reduces the risk of integration issues.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.atlassian.com/continuous-delivery/principles/continuous-integration-vs-delivery-vs-deployment">Atlassian - CI/CD</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 2. Docker -->
      <tr>
        <td>Docker</td>
        <td>A containerization platform that allows developers to package applications and their dependencies into lightweight, portable containers. Docker containers provide consistent environments across different stages of the development and deployment process, improving consistency and reducing conflicts.</td>
        <td><a href="https://docs.docker.com/get-started/overview/">Docker Documentation</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 3. Kubernetes -->
      <tr>
        <td>Kubernetes</td>
        <td>An open-source container orchestration tool used in DevOps environments to automate the deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. It ensures high availability and resilience of applications in production.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/home/">Kubernetes Documentation</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 4. Jenkins -->
      <tr>
        <td>Jenkins</td>
        <td>An open-source automation server widely used for Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment. Jenkins enables developers to automate the build, test, and deployment processes, making it a crucial tool in DevOps pipelines.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.jenkins.io/doc/">Jenkins Documentation</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 5. Git -->
      <tr>
        <td>Git</td>
        <td>A distributed version control system that enables developers to collaborate, track changes, and manage source code effectively. Git plays a crucial role in DevOps by providing a versioned and collaborative code repository.</td>
        <td><a href="https://git-scm.com/">Git SCM</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 6. Infrastructure as Code (IaC) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Infrastructure as Code (IaC)</td>
        <td>A DevOps practice of managing and provisioning infrastructure through machine-readable code, such as scripts or configuration files. IaC enables the automated and consistent deployment of infrastructure, reducing manual efforts and ensuring reproducibility.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.hashicorp.com/resources/what-is-infrastructure-as-code">HashiCorp - What is Infrastructure as Code</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 7. DevSecOps -->
      <tr>
        <td>DevSecOps</td>
        <td>An extension of DevOps that integrates security practices into the development and deployment process. DevSecOps aims to identify and address security issues early in the development lifecycle, making security an integral part of the continuous delivery pipeline.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.redhat.com/en/topics/devops/what-is-devsecops">Red Hat - DevSecOps</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 8. Microservices -->
      <tr>
        <td>Microservices</td>
        <td>A software architecture pattern where applications are divided into small, loosely coupled services. Microservices enable independent development, deployment, and scalability of each service, making it easier to maintain and evolve complex applications.</td>
        <td><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/architecture/microservices/">Microsoft - Microservices Architecture</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 9. Automation Testing -->
      <tr>
        <td>Automation Testing</td>
        <td>The practice of using automated tools to execute test cases and validate the functionality of software applications. In DevOps, automation testing is critical for ensuring rapid feedback and continuous quality assurance.</td>
        <td><a href="https://smartbear.com/learn/automated-testing/what-is-automated-testing/">SmartBear - Introduction to Test Automation</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 10. Cloud Computing -->
      <tr>
        <td>Cloud Computing</td>
        <td>A model for delivering computing resources (e.g., servers, storage, databases, networking) over the internet on a pay-as-you-go basis. Cloud computing is fundamental to DevOps as it provides scalable and flexible infrastructure to support continuous integration and deployment.</td>
        <td><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/what-is-cloud-computing/">Amazon Web Services (AWS) - What is Cloud Computing</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 11. Agile -->
      <tr>
        <td>Agile</td>
        <td>Agile is a set of software development principles and practices that emphasize collaboration, adaptability, and iterative development. Agile methodologies, such as Scrum and Kanban, promote close collaboration between development and operations teams, allowing them to respond to changes and deliver valuable software more frequently.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.agilealliance.org/agile101/">Agile Alliance - What is Agile?</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 12. Dark Launch -->
      <tr>
        <td>Dark Launch</td>
        <td>Dark Launch, also known as Feature Toggles or Feature Flags, is a DevOps technique where new features are deployed to production but remain hidden from users. This allows teams to gradually expose features to a subset of users for testing and validation, reducing the risk associated with large deployments and enabling faster feedback loops.</td>
        <td><a href="https://launchdarkly.com/blog/what-is-dark-launch/">LaunchDarkly - What is Dark Launch?</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 13. Test-driven Development (TDD) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Test-driven Development (TDD)</td>
        <td>Test-driven Development (TDD) is a software development practice where developers write automated tests before writing the actual code. TDD promotes writing small, focused units of code that satisfy the requirements of the test cases. This approach enhances code quality, encourages design simplicity, and ensures that the codebase remains reliable during changes.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.agilealliance.org/glossary/tdd/">Agile Alliance - Test-driven Development (TDD)</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 14. Provisioning -->
      <tr>
        <td>Provisioning</td>
        <td>Provisioning refers to the process of setting up and configuring resources, such as servers, virtual machines, or databases, to meet the requirements of an application or service. In DevOps, provisioning is often automated using Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tools to ensure consistency, speed up deployments, and reduce manual errors.</td>
        <td><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/cloud-adoption/getting-started/provisioning-infrastructure">Microsoft - Provisioning Infrastructure</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 15. Configuration Management -->
      <tr>
        <td>Configuration Management</td>
        <td>A practice of tracking, maintaining, and controlling the configuration settings and changes of software and systems. Configuration management ensures consistency, traceability, and enables efficient management of infrastructure.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.redhat.com/en/topics/devops/what-is-configuration-management">Red Hat - What is Configuration Management</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 16. Orchestration -->
      <tr>
        <td>Orchestration</td>
        <td>The automated arrangement, coordination, and management of various tasks, processes, and components within a DevOps workflow. Orchestration tools streamline complex workflows and ensure consistent execution.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.ibm.com/cloud/learn/orchestration">IBM Cloud - Orchestration</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 17. Deployment Pipeline -->
      <tr>
        <td>Deployment Pipeline</td>
        <td>A sequence of automated stages in a DevOps workflow that enables the continuous integration, testing, and deployment of code changes. The deployment pipeline ensures consistent and reliable software delivery.</td>
        <td><a href="https://continuousdelivery.com/patterns/continuous-deployment-pipeline/">Continuous Delivery - Deployment Pipeline</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 18. Canary Release -->
      <tr>
        <td>Canary Release</td>
        <td>A deployment technique where new code changes are gradually rolled out to a small subset of users or servers before being deployed to the entire infrastructure. This allows for monitoring and testing the new release's impact on a limited scale.</td>
        <td><a href="https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CanaryRelease.html">Martin Fowler - CanaryRelease</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 19. Version Control -->
      <tr>
        <td>Version Control</td>
        <td>A system that manages changes to source code and other files, allowing multiple contributors to collaborate on a project. Version control is fundamental in DevOps to track changes, facilitate collaboration, and maintain a history of code modifications.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/what-is-version-control">Atlassian - What is Version Control</a></td>
      </tr>
      
      <!-- 20. Chaos Engineering -->
      <tr>
        <td>Chaos Engineering</td>
        <td>A discipline that involves deliberately introducing failures and disruptions into a system to test its resilience and identify weaknesses. Chaos engineering helps organizations build more reliable and robust systems by uncovering potential issues before they occur in production.</td>
        <td><a href="https://principlesofchaos.org/">Principles of Chaos Engineering</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 21. Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)</td>
        <td>IaaS is a cloud computing service model that provides virtualized computing resources over the internet. It offers on-demand access to servers, storage, and networking, enabling organizations to scale their infrastructure without the need to invest in physical hardware.</td>
        <td><a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/overview/what-is-iaas/">Microsoft Azure - What is IaaS?</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 22. Service Level Agreement (SLA) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</td>
        <td>An SLA is a formal agreement between a service provider and a customer that outlines the expected level of service, including performance metrics, availability, and response times. SLAs are crucial in DevOps for defining service expectations and ensuring accountability.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.cio.com/article/243828/7-ways-to-boost-your-application-performance.html">CIO - Service Level Agreements</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 23. Workflow -->
      <tr>
        <td>Workflow</td>
        <td>Workflow in DevOps refers to the series of steps and processes that define the path of a task or project from initiation to completion. It encompasses the automation and coordination of tasks, ensuring efficient and predictable execution throughout the software development and delivery lifecycle.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.smartsheet.com/what-is-workflow-definition-and-importance">Smartsheet - What is Workflow</a></td>
      </tr>
  
      <!-- 24. Virtualization -->
      <tr>
        <td>Virtualization</td>
        <td>Virtualization is a technology that enables the creation of virtual instances of computer hardware, operating systems, or software applications. It allows multiple virtual environments to run on a single physical system, improving resource utilization, scalability, and flexibility in DevOps for testing, development, and production environments.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.vmware.com/topics/glossary/content/virtualization">VMware - Virtualization</a></td>
      </tr>
  
      <!-- 25. Quality Assurance (QA) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Quality Assurance (QA)</td>
        <td>Quality Assurance (QA) is the practice of systematically monitoring and evaluating the quality of a product or process. In DevOps, QA encompasses strategies, techniques, and tools to ensure that software applications meet predefined quality standards and functional requirements throughout the development and deployment pipeline.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.guru99.com/quality-assurance-tutorial.html">Guru99 - Quality Assurance Tutorial</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 26. DevOps Toolchain -->
      <tr>
        <td>DevOps Toolchain</td>
        <td>A DevOps toolchain refers to a set of tools and technologies used in the DevOps process to automate, manage, and streamline various stages of software development and deployment. It includes tools for version control, continuous integration, deployment, monitoring, and more.</td>
        <td><a href="https://devops.com/devops-tools/">DevOps.com - DevOps Tools</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 27. Elasticity -->
      <tr>
        <td>Elasticity</td>
        <td>Elasticity in DevOps refers to the ability of a system or infrastructure to dynamically scale up or down in response to changing workloads or demand. It allows resources such as servers, storage, and computing power to be provisioned or de-provisioned automatically to maintain optimal performance and cost-efficiency.</td>
        <td><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/what-is-elasticity/">Amazon Web Services (AWS) - What is Elasticity</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 28. MongoDB -->
      <tr>
        <td>MongoDB</td>
        <td>MongoDB is a popular NoSQL database management system that is often used in DevOps and modern application development. MongoDB stores data in flexible, schema-less documents, making it well-suited for handling unstructured or semi-structured data. It is known for its scalability, high availability, and support for distributed database architectures.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.mongodb.com/what-is-mongodb">MongoDB - What is MongoDB</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 29. Blue-Green Deployment -->
      <tr>
        <td>Blue-Green Deployment</td>
        <td>Blue-Green Deployment is a deployment strategy that involves maintaining two separate environments, one "blue" (production) and one "green" (new version). The new version is deployed to the green environment and tested, and then traffic is switched from blue to green, minimizing downtime and risk during updates.</td>
        <td><a href="https://martinfowler.com/bliki/BlueGreenDeployment.html">Martin Fowler - Blue-Green Deployment</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 30. Cluster -->
      <tr>
        <td>Cluster</td>
        <td>In DevOps, a cluster refers to a group of interconnected servers, nodes, or instances that work together to distribute workloads, improve fault tolerance, and enhance the performance of applications. Clustering is used to achieve high availability, scalability, and reliability in distributed systems.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/en-au/learning/network-layer-attacks/what-is-a-cluster/">Cloudflare - What is a Cluster</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 31. Artifact Repository -->
      <tr>
        <td>Artifact Repository</td>
        <td>An Artifact Repository is a centralized location for storing and managing software artifacts, such as binary files, libraries, and dependencies. It plays a critical role in DevOps for versioning and sharing artifacts across the software development and deployment lifecycle.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Repository">JFrog - Artifact Repository</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 32. Terraform Provider -->
      <tr>
        <td>Terraform Provider</td>
        <td>A Terraform provider is a plugin that allows Terraform to interact with specific APIs or services, enabling the creation, management, and deletion of resources in those services. Providers are used to extend Terraform's capabilities to various platforms.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/index.html">Terraform Providers Documentation</a></td>
      </tr>
      
      <!-- 33. Service Mesh -->
      <tr>
        <td>Service Mesh</td>
        <td>A Service Mesh is a dedicated infrastructure layer that handles communication and network interactions between microservices. It provides features like load balancing, security, and observability to microservices-based applications.</td>
        <td><a href="https://istio.io/latest/docs/concepts/what-is-istio/">Istio - What is a Service Mesh?</a></td>
      </tr>
      
      <!-- 34. Zero Trust Security Model -->
      <tr>
        <td>Zero Trust Security Model</td>
        <td>The Zero Trust Security Model is an approach where no entity, whether inside or outside the network, is trusted by default. DevOps teams use this model to enhance security by verifying and validating every access request.</td>
        <td><a href="https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-207.pdf">NIST - Zero Trust Architecture</a></td>
      </tr>
       
      <!-- 35. GitOps -->
      <tr>
        <td>GitOps</td>
        <td>GitOps is a DevOps practice where the entire infrastructure and application state is stored in a Git repository. Changes to the infrastructure are managed through Git commits and are automatically applied to the environment.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.weave.works/technologies/gitops/">Weaveworks - GitOps</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 36. Secret Management -->
      <tr>
        <td>Secret Management</td>
        <td>Secret Management involves securely storing, accessing, and distributing sensitive information such as passwords and API keys. DevOps teams use secret management tools to protect sensitive data in their workflows.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.hashicorp.com/resources/secrets-management">HashiCorp Vault - Secrets Management</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 37. Immutable Infrastructure -->
      <tr>
        <td>Immutable Infrastructure</td>
        <td>Immutable Infrastructure is an approach where infrastructure components, such as servers, are never modified after their initial setup. Instead, when changes are required, new instances are created and the old ones are replaced. This approach improves consistency and reduces configuration drift.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.hashicorp.com/resources/what-is-immutable-infrastructure">HashiCorp - Immutable Infrastructure</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 38. Container -->
      <tr>
        <td>Containers</td>
        <td>Containers are a standardized packaging format that encapsulates all the necessary components to run software, including the application code and its dependencies. They provide a consistent and reliable way to execute applications across diverse computing environments.</td>
        <td>Reference: <a href="https://www.docker.com/resources/what-container">Docker - What is a Container</a></td>
      </tr>
       
      <!-- 39. Rollback -->
      <tr>
        <td>Rollback</td>
        <td>Rollback is a DevOps process that involves reverting to a previous version of a software application or system configuration in case of issues or failures. It is used to restore stability and functionality to the system by undoing recent changes.</td>
        <td>Reference: <a href="https://dev.to/rhymu8354/the-devops-handbook-by-gene-kim-2e4a">DevOps Handbook - Gene Kim</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 40. Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR)</td>
        <td>Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR) is a key performance metric in DevOps that measures the average time it takes to restore a system or application to full functionality after a failure or incident. A lower MTTR indicates faster incident resolution and better system reliability.</td>
        <td>Reference: <a href="https://www.atlassian.com/incident-management/kpis/mean-time-to-recovery-mttr">Atlassian - Mean Time to Recovery (MTTR)</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 41. Ingress Controller -->
      <tr>
        <td>Ingress Controller</td>
        <td>An Ingress Controller is a component in Kubernetes that manages external access to services within the cluster. It acts as a reverse proxy and allows for routing and load balancing of incoming traffic to different services.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/ingress/">Kubernetes Ingress</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 42. Prometheus Monitoring -->
      <tr>
        <td>Prometheus Monitoring</td>
        <td>Prometheus is an open-source monitoring and alerting toolkit used to collect and store metrics from applications and infrastructure. It offers a powerful query language and visualization tools for monitoring DevOps environments.</td>
        <td><a href="https://prometheus.io/docs/introduction/overview/">Prometheus - Introduction</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 43. Horizontal Pod Autoscaling (HPA) -->
      <tr>
        <td>Horizontal Pod Autoscaling (HPA)</td>
        <td>Horizontal Pod Autoscaling (HPA) is a Kubernetes feature that automatically adjusts the number of pods in a deployment or replica set based on CPU or custom metrics. It ensures optimal resource utilization and application performance.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/run-application/horizontal-pod-autoscale/">Kubernetes HPA</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 44. Kubernetes StatefulSet -->
      <tr>
        <td>Kubernetes StatefulSet</td>
        <td>Kubernetes StatefulSet is a workload API object used for managing stateful applications in Kubernetes clusters. It provides guarantees about the order and uniqueness of pods, making it suitable for databases and other stateful services.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/statefulset/">Kubernetes StatefulSet Documentation</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 45. Kubeconfig -->
      <tr>
        <td>Kubeconfig</td>
        <td>Kubeconfig is a configuration file that contains authentication and cluster information for connecting to a Kubernetes cluster. DevOps teams use kubeconfig files to access and manage Kubernetes clusters.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/organize-cluster-access-kubeconfig/">Kubernetes - Kubeconfig</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 46. StatefulSet -->
      <tr>
        <td>StatefulSet</td>
        <td>A StatefulSet is a workload API object in Kubernetes designed for managing stateful applications. It provides guarantees about the ordering and uniqueness of Pods, making it suitable for databases and other stateful services.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/statefulset/">Kubernetes - StatefulSets</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 47. Service -->
      <tr>
        <td>Service</td>
        <td>Kubernetes Services provide an abstraction for routing traffic to a group of Pods. Services enable load balancing and make it possible to access applications consistently within the cluster.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/">Kubernetes - Services</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 48. Helm -->
      <tr>
        <td>Helm</td>
        <td>Helm is a package manager for Kubernetes that simplifies the deployment and management of applications. It allows you to define, install, and upgrade even the most complex Kubernetes applications.</td>
        <td><a href="https://helm.sh/">Helm - Official Website</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 49. Pod -->
      <tr>
        <td>Pod</td>
        <td>In Kubernetes, a Pod is the smallest deployable unit that can contain one or more containers. Pods are used to encapsulate and manage containers within the cluster.</td>
        <td><a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/pods/">Kubernetes - Pods</a></td>
      </tr>

      <!-- 50. OpenStack -->
      <tr>
        <td>OpenStack</td>
        <td>OpenStack is an open-source platform designed for building on-premises cloud infrastructures. It provides a set of software tools and components for creating and managing private and public cloud environments. OpenStack enables organizations to deploy and manage scalable and flexible cloud services within their own data centers.</td>
        <td><a href="https://www.openstack.org/">OpenStack - Official Website</a></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
